        routeDescription: "Via the A6 towards Paris, exit at Bercy/Gare de Lyon.",
        introduction: "The taxi from Fontainebleau to Paris Gare de Lyon is the premium alternative to the Transilien R commuter train, particularly suited to travellers with TGV connections, bulky luggage, or tight schedules. Gare de Lyon is the departure point for TGV high-speed trains to Lyon, Marseille, the Cote d'Azur, Switzerland and Italy. It is also the terminus of the Transilien R line serving Fontainebleau-Avon, but with a 40- to 50-minute journey standing up and no guaranteed seat during peak hours, the taxi is the preferred choice of business travellers, families with children, and passengers with reduced mobility. The 60-minute door-to-door transfer ensures you arrive at the station relaxed and on time. The Gare de Lyon area also serves the Bercy neighbourhood (AccorHotels Arena, Cour Saint-Emilion with its restaurants and cinemas) and is a major hub in the Paris transport network, with connections to metro lines 1 and 14 as well as RER lines A and D.",
        itineraire: "Your driver takes the N7 and then the A6 motorway heading towards Paris. As you approach the capital, the exit at Bercy/Gare de Lyon is reached via the inner ring road (peripherique interieur) or the right-bank express road (voie rapide rive droite). You are dropped off directly at the station forecourt -- on the mainline side or the suburban side, depending on which train you are catching. Allow 60 minutes under normal traffic conditions. During rush hours (7:30am to 9:30am, 5pm to 7:30pm), plan for up to 1 hour and 20 minutes. Tolls amount to approximately 6 euros and are included in the fare. An alternative route through Evry and the D306 is available in case of a bottleneck on the A6 near Evry-Lisses.",
        conseils: "Arrive at the station 20 minutes before your TGV departure (30 minutes during holiday periods). TGV platform numbers are displayed on the screens 20 minutes before departure time. Le Train Bleu, the classified restaurant on the first floor of Hall 1, is well worth a detour for its stunning Belle Epoque decor and traditional French cuisine. For return journeys, the last Transilien train to Fontainebleau departs around 10:30pm -- after that hour, the taxi is your only option. If you have a connecting flight from CDG, a taxi from Gare de Lyon to CDG is faster and more reliable than taking the RER B (35 minutes versus 45 minutes with fewer uncertainties).",
