        description: "Montereau-Fault-Yonne, at the confluence of the Seine and Yonne rivers, is 70 min from Paris.",
        routeDescription: "Via the A5 then A6 motorway towards Paris.",
        introduction: "Montereau-Fault-Yonne occupies a spectacular position at the confluence of the Seine and Yonne rivers, a strategic location that made it a site of momentous historical events. It was here in 1419 that the Duke of Burgundy, Jean sans Peur (John the Fearless), was assassinated on the bridge, an act that triggered the Anglo-Burgundian alliance and fundamentally altered the course of the Hundred Years' War. Napoleon Bonaparte won his last military victory on French soil at Montereau on 18 February 1814, defeating Austrian and Wurttemberg forces in a battle commemorated by an equestrian statue in the town. Today, Montereau is a major economic hub in southern Seine-et-Marne, home to a substantial industrial zone (Schneider Electric, logistics centres), an active river port on the Seine, and a strategic position at the crossroads of the A5 motorway and the D606. The town of 20,000 inhabitants is undergoing significant urban renewal and modernisation. Residents rely on taxis to Paris for professional trips, medical appointments, and travel during hours when the Transilien commuter train service is unavailable or inconvenient.",
        itineraire: "Your driver departs Montereau either via the D606 heading north or directly onto the A5 motorway (Autoroute de l'Est). The A5 connects to the Francilienne ring road and then the A6 at Lieusaint/Senart, before continuing towards Paris via the southern peripherique. Allow 70 minutes under normal traffic conditions. During rush hours, plan for up to 1 hour and 35 minutes, primarily due to congestion between Melun-Senart and Paris. Tolls amount to approximately 8 euros and are included in the fare. An alternative route via the D606 through Fontainebleau and the A6 south is available should there be a bottleneck on the A5.",
        conseils: "The confluence of the Seine and Yonne rivers is a remarkable natural spectacle, best viewed from the medieval bridge. The collegiate church of Notre-Dame-et-Saint-Loup (15th century) rewards a visit, as does the Faience Museum and the former Montereau earthenware manufactory (19th century), which bear witness to the town's rich industrial past. The Saturday morning market on Place du Marche is one of the largest in the area and an excellent place to sample local produce. Montereau station provides Transilien commuter trains to Paris (55 to 60 minutes), but with limited frequency. For travel to the business parks of Senart or the Melun-Val-de-Seine area, the taxi is often the most rational choice in terms of both time and convenience.",
        comparaisonTransport: "Transilien R from Montereau: €11-14, 55-65 min, reduced frequency (6-8 direct trains/day). Taxi at €105-135: 70 min door-to-door. For 3-4 passengers (€26-45 each), competitive, especially off-peak or weekends when trains are rare.",
